<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Former Christian Coalition Director, ACLU President Discuss Church, State at Frey Symposium</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette and Tom Evelyn
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 27, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="http://news.ucf.edu/resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE925/en_US/Frey-crowd sty.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>Audience members packed the Pegasus Ballroom at the UCF Student Union on Monday night to hear Ralph Reed and Nadine Strossen speak at &#147;Church and State: Blurring the Line,&#148; a daylong symposium held by the Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400414b7bd579010692fefcde007e4b">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
							
								<h3>Story Images</h3>
								<ul id="story_images">
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400414b7bd579010692fefcde007e4b&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=0">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE925/en_US/Frey-Reed.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400414b7bd579010692fefcde007e4b&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=1">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE925/en_US/Frey-Strossen.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400414b7bd579010692fefcde007e4b&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=2">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE925/en_US/Frey-Hitt.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			</ul><p  class="note">Click thumbnails for full-size images.</p>
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:dlanier@mail.ucf.edu">Drew Lanier</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-3753</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.cas.ucf.edu/politicalscience/loufrey/">Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Ralph Reed and Nadine Strossen support the separation of church and state. Its only in the details where they disagree.</p><p>The former executive director of the Christian Coalition and the national president of the American Civil Liberties Union gave the keynote addresses and answered questions Monday night at the conclusion of Church and State: Blurring the Line, a daylong symposium by the UCF Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government.</p><p /><p /><p>Reed and Strossen addressed prayer in schools, cases involving the display of the Ten Commandments at government buildings and the teaching of evolution and intelligent design, while taking questions from a student panel and audience members in the Pegasus Ballroom at the UCF Student Union.</p><p /><p /><p>Expressing a need for civil debate on the topic, the two seemed to find more common ground on many of the issues than the audience may have expected. Still, they differed on some definitions.</p><p /><p /><p>I support the separation of church and state  primarily to protect the church from the state, not the state from the church, Reed said, adding that faith should be accommodated in the public sphere.</p><p /><p /><p>The subject is more accurately described as the separation of religion and government, Strossen said, adding that the First Amendment protects both equally and that the courts have actually been very supportive of accommodation.</p><p /><p /><p>The symposium began Monday morning with a panel presentation on how policymakers view church and state issues. Speakers included U.S. Rep. Ric Keller, R-Orlando, and Orange County Mayor Rich Crotty. </p><p /><p>Rabbi Richard S. Chizever, of Temple Israel in Longwood; Joel Hunter, senior pastor of Northland, A Church Distributed, in Longwood; and Imam Muhammad Musri, president of the Islamic Society of Central Florida, spoke during a forum on how different faiths perceive church and state issues.</p><p /><p>The symposium also featured <place /><placename />George</placename /> <placename />Mason</placename /> <placename />University</placename /></place /> professor and author Jeremy D. Mayer, the author of Running on Race: Racial Politics in Presidential Campaigns, 1960-2000 and 9-11: The Giant Awakens.</p><p /><p>Attorneys David Friedman, who represented the ACLU in a Ten Commandments case, and Steven L. Micas, who represented <place /><city />Chesterfield County</city />, <state />Va.</state /></place />, in a separate case involving religion and local government, also spoke.</p><p /><p>Other speakers included retired Lutheran minister John McCollister, author of God and the Oval Office: The Religious Faith of Our 43 Presidents, Michael Cromartie, vice president of the Ethics and Public Policy Center in Washington, D.C., and Circuit Judge Clayton Simmons of Floridas 18th Judicial Circuit.</p><p /><p /><p>The Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government is a nonpartisan organization that promotes civic education for students and other <place />Central Florida</place /> residents. Frey represented <place />Central Florida</place /> in Congress from 1969 to 1979.</p><p /><p>The institutes next symposium, A Day with the Florida Governors, will bring together several of the states past governors on March 27. </p><p /><p>More information about the Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government is available at <a href="http://www.loufrey.org/">www.loufrey.org</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
